{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654507"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18616"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18616"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.05,0.1,0.52,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79497"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11348"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18616"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64819"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10223"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26342"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27191"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79497"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESynovial fluid is essential for normal joint function. It is produced by cells in the synovial membrane and fills the joint cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main component responsible for its lubricating properties?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Albumin","Collagen","Fibronectin","Hyaluronic acid","Proteoglycans"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyaluronic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is the key component that gives synovial fluid its viscous, lubricating properties. It is synthesised by type B synoviocytes in the synovial membrane and secreted into the joint space. The high molecular weight and unique chemical structure of hyaluronic acid creates the characteristic viscosity that enables efficient joint lubrication and shock absorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollagen\u003C/strong\u003E - While important in joint structure, it is found in cartilage and connective tissue rather than synovial fluid\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibronectin\u003C/strong\u003E - This glycoprotein is involved in cell adhesion but does not contribute significantly to joint lubrication\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin\u003C/strong\u003E - Though present in synovial fluid as an ultrafiltrate of plasma, it does not provide lubricating properties\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProteoglycans\u003C/strong\u003E - These are primarily found in cartilage matrix rather than synovial fluid\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESynovial fluid is an ultrafiltrate of plasma with added hyaluronic acid, which creates its characteristic viscosity and enables smooth joint movement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Synovial fluid contains hyaluronic acid which provides lubrication and shock absorption in joints.","Synovial fluid is an ultrafiltrate of plasma with added hyaluronic acid produced by synovial membrane cells.","Normal synovial fluid is clear, viscous, and contains few cells (\u003C200 white blood cells/\u00b5L)."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64819"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18616"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64819"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T20:22:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T20:23:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11348"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79497"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}